"Don't tell anyone about this," he said. "Go and show yourself to the priest. Offer the sacrifices prescribed by Moses. That will be a testimony to the priest and the people that you are 'clean'."
But the man went out and began to proclaim it freely, and to spread the news so widely that Jesus could no longer enter a town openly. He remained outside in secluded places, but people from all quarters continued to flock to him.
Jesus heals a man who couldn't walk.
A few days later, Jesus again entered Capernaum, and it was heard that He had returned home.
The people gathered so closely together that there was no room left, not even near the door. And Jesus was preaching the word to them.
Four of those who came were carrying a man who could not walk.
But they could not get near Jesus because of the crowd. So they made an opening in the roof above Jesus and, after removing some tiles, they lowered the mat on which the paralyzed man was lying.
Jesus saw their faith, and he said to the man, "Child, your sins are forgiven."
Some of the disciples of the law were sitting there. They were thinking,
Why is this man talking like this? He's saying something very evil! Only God forgives sins!
Immediately Jesus knew in his spirit that they were discussing among themselves what they might say. He said to them, "Why are you discussing what you might say? "
Is it easier to say to this man, 'Your sins are forgiven,' or to say, 'Get up, take your bed and walk'?
"I want you to know that the Son of Man has authority on earth to forgive sins." Then Jesus spoke to the man who couldn't walk.
He said, "Arise, take your mat and go to your house."
The man rose and took up his mat. Then he walked away, while everyone watched. All the people were amazed. They praised God and said, "We have never seen anything like this before!" Jesus chooses Levi.
And Jesus went out again beside the Sea of Galilee; and a great multitude gathered around Him, so He began to teach them.
As Jesus walked along, he saw Levi son of Alphaeus sitting at the tax collector‚Äôs booth. ‚ÄúFollow me,‚Äù he told him, and Levi got up and followed him.
Later, Jesus was dining at Levi's house, and many tax collectors and "sinners" were eating with him and his disciples. They were part of the large crowds that were following Jesus.
There were some Pharisees who were teachers of the law. They saw him eating with "sinners" and tax collectors. So they asked his disciples, "Why does he eat with tax collectors and 'sinners'?"
Jesus heard this and said to them, "Those who are well have no need of a physician, but those who are sick; I came not to call the righteous, but sinners." He was also asked about fasting.
The disciples of John and the Pharisees often fasted. Some people came to Jesus and asked him, "Why do the disciples of John and the Pharisees fast, but your disciples do not fast?"
Jesus answered, "How can the guests of the bridegroom fast while the bridegroom is with them? As long as they have the bridegroom with them, they cannot fast."
But the day will come when the bridegroom will be taken from them. On that day they will fast.
People do not tear a piece from a new garment and patch it onto an old one. If they did, the new piece would pull away from the old, making the tear worse.
People do not pour new wine into old wineskins. If they do, the wine will burst the skins, and both the wine and the skins will be lost. Instead, they pour new wine into new wineskins." Jesus is Lord of the Sabbath.
On one of the sabbath days Jesus was going through the grainfields, and as his disciples walked along, they began to pick some heads of grain.
The Pharisees said to Jesus, "Look! Your disciples are doing what is unlawful on the Sabbath."
He replied, "Have you never read what David did when he and his men were hungry? They needed food."
That was when Abiathar was high priest. David entered the house of God and ate the showbread, which was only allowed for the priests to eat. He also gave some to his men.
Jesus said to them, "The Sabbath was made for man, not man for the Sabbath."
"The Son of Man is Lord even of the Sabbath."
Healing on Saturday
And another time Jesus entered the synagogue. There was a man with a withered and paralyzed hand.
Some Pharisees were trying to find fault with Jesus. They watched him closely. They wanted to see whether he would heal the man on the Sabbath.
Jesus spoke to the man with the weak and distorted hand, saying, "Rise up before everyone."
So Jesus asked them, "What does the law say? What should we do on the Sabbath? Should we do good or evil? Should we save a life or destroy one?" But they did not answer.
Jesus looked around at them with anger. He was greatly distressed because their hearts were hard. Then he said to the man, "Stretch out your hand." He stretched it out, and his hand was restored.
Then the Pharisees went out and began to plot with the Herodians against Jesus, how to destroy Him. The multitudes were following Jesus.
Jesus and his disciples went to the Sea of Galilee, and a large crowd from Galilee followed him.
The people heard about all that Jesus was doing. And many came to him, from Judea, Jerusalem, Idumea, beyond the Jordan, the region of Tyre and Sidon.
And because of the crowds, Jesus asked his disciples to prepare a small boat for him, so that he would not be crushed by the people.
Jesus healed many people. The sick pressed forward to touch him.
When the evil spirits saw Jesus, they fell down before Him. And they cried out, saying, "You are the Son of God!"
But Jesus commanded them not to tell who he was. Jesus appoints the twelve apostles.
Jesus went up a mountain and called to him those whom he desired, and they came to him.
He appointed twelve, whom he also named apostles, that they might be with him and he might send them out to preach.
And they had authority to cast out demons.
So Jesus appointed twelve, whom he also named apostles, and among them was Simon, whom he named Peter.
There were Jacob son of Zebedee and his brother John. Jesus gave them the name Boanerges, which means Sons of Thunder.
And Andrew, and Philip, and Bartholomew, and Matthew, and Thomas, and James the son of Alphaeus, and Thaddaeus, and Simon the Zealot.
Judas Iscariot was also among them. He was the one who would later betray Jesus to his enemies. Jesus and Beelzebul.
Jesus entered a house. And a large crowd gathered as well. The crowd was so large that Jesus and his disciples could not even eat.
His family heard about it. They went to take care of him. They said, "He has lost his mind."
There were some teachers of the law who came down from Jerusalem. They said, "He is driven by Beelzebul, the prince of demons, to drive out demons."
So Jesus called them and spoke to them in parables, saying, "How can Satan cast out Satan?"
If a kingdom fights against itself, it will not endure.
If the family is divided, it cannot last.
